,"1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1379":"1379","1368":"1368","1332":"1332","2 July 1361":"2 juli 1361","1320":"1320","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","Freeford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Freeford, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Fulford, Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stafford, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1315–2 July 1361":"1315–2 July 1361","1315–1361":"1315–1361","1320–1368":"1320–1368","1305–1380":"1305–1380","–1368":"–1368","–1379":"–1379","1290–1332":"1290–1332","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","1379":"1379","1368":"1368","1332":"1332","2 July 1361":"2 July 1361","1320":"1320","1361":"1361","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","Freeford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Freeford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Fulford, Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Freford,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name apparently from a lost place in Devon, recorded as  <i>Wreyford</i>, 1344 in   Patent Rolls   (Devon)."],"variants":[{"name":"Wrayford","meanings":["English:  see  Wreford  ."]},{"name":"Patent Rolls","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from the Middle English female personal name  <i>Godyeve</i>,  <i>Godive</i>,  <i>Godif</i> (Old English  <i>Godgifu</i>, latinized as  <i>Godiva</i>). It became confused with another Middle English female personal name  <i>Godith</i> (Old English  <i>Godgȳð</i>);  see  Goodey  , and compare Godyf widow of John Clare, alias Goditha Clare de Strode in   Assize Rolls   (Kent). (ii) status name, nickname, occasionally perhaps from Middle English  <i>godwif</i> ‘virtuous woman; mistress of a household’, often used as a courtesy title for married women of relatively humble social status.  Compare  Hussey   (3) (from  <i>hus(e)wif</i>) and   Goodman  . For obvious reasons it was mainly borne by women, such as Nota Godwyf, 1311 in   Colchester Court Rolls  , and Margaret Godewyf, 1374 in   Feet of Fines   (Hunts). The bearing of the name by a man, such as John Godewyf, 1413 in   Patent Rolls   (Glatton, Hunts), can be explained either as an ironic nickname or perhaps through being surnamed from the mother’s title. Alternatively, because  <i>goodwife</i> was generally reduced to  <i>goody(f)</i>, the relationship name in (i) may have re-etymologized as ‘goodwife’, and  <i>Godewyf</i> and  <i>Goodwife</i> as hereditary surnames are hypercorrections of  <i>Goodiff</i> and  <i>Goodeve</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John de Freford, Knight, Chiveler was born in 1315, in Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of William II Freford. He had at least 4 daughters with Margaret Grendon. He died on 2 July 1361, in his hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1315–2 July 1361":"1315–2. juuli 1361","1315–1361":"1315–1361","1320–1368":"1320–1368","1305–1380":"1305–1380","–1368":"–1368","–1379":"–1379","1290–1332":"1290